        Regular physical activity has been recognized to confer health benefits since antiquity
        [<ENAMEX TYPE="LAW">1</ENAMEX>]. However, for most of humankind, voluntary discretion over whether or not to exercise
        is a recent phenomenon limited to advanced industrialized societies.
        A large <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">body</ENAMEX> of epidemiological literature consistently documents greater longevity in
        <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">persons</ENAMEX> who are physically active on a near-daily basis, and reveals inverse relationships
        <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">between</TIMEX> levels of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">daily</TIMEX> exercise and incidence of major chronic disorders such as obesity
        [<ENAMEX TYPE="LAW">2</ENAMEX>], hypertension [<ENAMEX TYPE="LAW">3</ENAMEX>], <ENAMEX TYPE="DISEASE">diabetes</ENAMEX> [<ENAMEX TYPE="LAW">4</ENAMEX>], ischemic <ENAMEX TYPE="DISEASE">heart disease</ENAMEX>, and all causes of mortality
        [<NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">5,6,7,8,9,10,11,12</NUMEX>]. From a public health perspective, there is little question that even
        modest increases in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">daily</TIMEX> activities such as walking or stair climbing would have important
        positive consequences in reducing the burden of <ENAMEX TYPE="DISEASE">illness</ENAMEX>.
        However, knowledge of the likely health benefits accruing to the physically active so
